        <headline>Special Weather Statement issued April 5 at 5:59AM CDT by NWS Paducah KY</headline>
        <description>At 558 AM CDT, Doppler radar was tracking a strong thunderstorm near
Big Rock, or 10 miles northeast of Dover, moving northeast at 45
mph. The storm was part of a broader line that will bring more heavy
rain and lightning to the area, increasing and expanding the
particularly dangerous flooding risk.

HAZARD...Wind gusts up to 50 mph and pea size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Gusty winds could knock down tree limbs and blow around
unsecured objects. Minor hail damage to vegetation is
possible.

Locations impacted include...
Justice, Graham, Rockcastle, Everett, Cadiz, Central City, Pembroke,
Wranglers Campground, Energy Lake Campground, Bremen, Hopkinsville,
Powderly, Turkey Bay, Clifty, Herndon, Hawkins, Greenville, Oak
Grove, Linton, and Elkton.

This includes the following highways...
Interstate 24 in Kentucky between Mile Markers 58 and 92.
Western Kentucky Parkway between Mile Markers 45 and 64.
Pennyrile Parkway between Mile Markers 1 and 27.
</description>
        <instruction>If outdoors, consider seeking shelter inside a building.

Torrential rainfall is also occurring with this storm and may lead to
localized flooding. Do not drive your vehicle through flooded
roadways.

Frequent cloud to ground lightning is occurring with this storm.
Lightning can strike 10 miles away from a thunderstorm. Seek a safe
shelter inside a building or vehicle.</instruction>
